      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "John Stuart Mill would argue that state intervention in speech is a dangerous form of \"paternalism\" that assumes the government knows better than the public how to handle truth, which is a recipe for tyranny. Libertarian theorists like Robert Nozick would frame this as a fundamental violation of individual liberty, asserting that the state has no legitimate authority to censor speech, even if it is harmful, because doing so treats citizens as children rather than autonomous adults. The core philosophical flaw in regulation is that the state cannot remain neutral; it will inevitably favor its own political interests or the preferences of the powerful, thereby corrupting the very marketplace of ideas it claims to protect.",
